Author:
Vol / Page:  2024
Edition:
Quote:  Hut (h&ubreve.t), n. [Add.] 2. A house for shearers or other labourers on a station; as, the men's hut, there shearers' hut. This is sometimes a large, permanent structure of wood, brick, or stone. -->1898 Morris AE 207 Hut, n the cottage of a shepherd or a miner. The word is English but is especially common in Australia, and does not there connote squalor or meanness. The `Men's Hut' on a station is the building occupied by the male employees. [1844]
